{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5cda561a-eba8-43e9-9bd1-cc7f1d514002","content":"Yes, you'll hit compatibility issues. Here's the breakdown:\n\n**Framework support dropped in MSTest v3:**\n- **`net5.0`** — ❌ not supported (EOL). Migrate to `net6.0` or later.\n- **`netcoreapp3.1`** — ❌ not supported (EOL). Migrate to `net6.0` or later.\n- **`net462`** — ✅ still supported.\n\nMSTest v3 requires **.NET 6.0+** for the modern .NET side and **.NET Framework 4.6.2+** for legacy.\n\n**Other MSTest v3 changes to be aware of:**\n1. **Package consolidation** — you can replace `MSTest.TestFramework` + `MSTest.TestAdapter` with a single `MSTest` meta-package.\n2. **Behavioral breaking changes** — e.g., `DataRow` type-matching is stricter, some assertions have updated defaults.\n\n**To migrate**, you'd need to update your `TargetFrameworks` first:\n```xml\n<TargetFrameworks>net6.0;net462</TargetFrameworks>\n```\nThen upgrade the packages. Want me to make these changes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"04294a1f-fa42-4292-a3df-dacb4c3a95db","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user's project multi-targets `net5.0`, `net462`, and `netcoreapp3.1`. They want to migrate to MSTest v3.\n\nMSTest v3 has some important compatibility changes:\n\n1. **Dropped framework support**: MSTest v3 dropped support for older target frameworks. Specifically, MSTest v3 requires at least:\n   - .NET 6.0+ (for .NET Core/modern .NET)\n   - .NET Framework 4.6.2+ (this one should be fine since they have net462)\n   \n   Wait, let me think more carefully. \n\nMSTest v3 dropped support for `netcoreapp3.1` and `net5.0`, so the user will need to either remove those target frameworks or stick with MSTest v2. The framework only supports .NET Framework 4.6.2+ and .NET 6.0+.\n\nOn the packaging side, MSTest v3 consolidates the separate `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` packages into a single `MSTest` package, which simplifies dependency management. Beyond the TFM compatibility issue, there are some behavioral and API breaking changes, but the target framework mismatch is the main blocker here.","outputTokens":692,"requestId":"0C02:C1990:61D8DF3:6B349F7:69F01F0D"},"id":"13e743e2-425b-4c37-b9c1-2cc82495d369","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:44:43.742Z","parentId":"4f82c7a5-99c7-4ad8-9b15-32c1ee3da4c2"}
